Initially I included CURIEs in HAL with a _curies property, and used it in
=
some examples. I&#39;ve since removed it on the basis that it is not
particular=
ly useful, people apparently found the colon syntax
confusing/alarming.

Th=
ere are a few ways to achieve discoverable rels. The first is to simply
use=
 URIs for the link relations. Another approach is to make sure that the
doc=
umentation for your application is linked from the entry point of your
app,=
 and explains where the rel tokens can be found in the documentation
(i.e. =
URI generation).

Probably the &#39;best&#39; approach would be to have a URI templ=
ate presented at
the entry point which instructs clients how CURIEs should =
be built, i.e:

request:
GET /

response:
{
...
  &quot;_links&quot; : {
    &quot;curie&quot;:=
 { &quot;href&quot;: &quot;http://example.com/rels/{relation}&quot;, &quot;title&quot;: &quot;ex&quot; }
  },
...
}=


which would instruct the client on how to resolve the &#39;CURIEs&#39; elsewhere =
in
your application, e.g:

{
...
  &quot;_links&quot; : {
    &quot;ex:foo&quot; : { &quot;href&quot;: &quot;/=
bar&quot; }
  },
...
}

This uses URI templates, and the title property of the l=
ink to emulate
CURIEs without having to burden everyone using HAL with an e=
xtra CURIE
mechanism.

